  {"id": "seg_00079", "translation": "4.2  Extremum Problems (Extremum)"},
  {"id": "seg_00080", "translation": "People always tend to be fascinated by things that are a bit further away — things at the extremes."},
  {"id": "seg_00081", "translation": "Similarly, the maximum and minimum values of a function naturally attract great interest. After all, extrema are enormously useful in everyday life."},
  {"id": "seg_00082", "translation": "To tackle extremum problems, derivatives can be a tremendous help. First, let's clarify a few concepts related to extrema."},
  {"id": "seg_00083", "translation": "Local Maximum: If the inequality "},
  {"id": "seg_00084", "translation": " holds for all x in some open interval containing c, then "},
  {"id": "seg_00085", "translation": " is a local maximum of the function "},
  {"id": "seg_00086", "translation": ". A local maximum is sometimes also called a relative maximum (Relative Maximum)."},
  {"id": "seg_00087", "translation": "Where there is local, there is global."},
  {"id": "seg_00088", "translation": "Global Maximum: If the inequality "},
  {"id": "seg_00089", "translation": " holds for all x, then "},
  {"id": "seg_00090", "translation": " is the global maximum of the function "},
  {"id": "seg_00091", "translation": ". The global maximum is sometimes called the absolute maximum (Absolute Maximum)."},
  {"id": "seg_00092", "translation": "Let's elaborate on these two concepts. By \"local,\" we mean that as long as the inequality "},
  {"id": "seg_00093", "translation": " holds on even a very small interval,"},
  {"id": "seg_00094", "translation": " qualifies as a local maximum."},
  {"id": "seg_00095", "translation": "For example, if we treat the altitude above sea level on Earth as a function, then the summit of each of the Five Sacred Mountains is a local maximum. At the same time, every step of the staircase you climb to get home — or even the height of the slippers you left on the floor — is also a local maximum. Mount Everest, however, is the global maximum of this function."},
  {"id": "seg_00096", "translation": "The concept of a minimum is the mirror image of the maximum."},
  {"id": "seg_00097", "translation": "Chapter 4 | What Are Derivatives Good For?"},
  {"id": "seg_00098", "translation": "Local Minimum: If the inequality "},
  {"id": "seg_00099", "translation": " holds for all x in some open interval containing c, then "},
  {"id": "seg_00100", "translation": " is a local minimum of the function "},
  {"id": "seg_00101", "translation": ". A local minimum is sometimes also called a relative minimum (Relative Minimum)."},
  {"id": "seg_00102", "translation": "Global Minimum: If the inequality "},
  {"id": "seg_00103", "translation": " holds for all x, then "},
  {"id": "seg_00104", "translation": " is the global minimum of the function "},
  {"id": "seg_00105", "translation": ". The global minimum is sometimes called the absolute minimum (Absolute Minimum)."},
  {"id": "seg_00106", "translation": "Now that we understand the concept of extrema, we can explore how to find them."},
  {"id": "seg_00107", "translation": "To study how to find extrema, we first need to establish their existence. So it is worthwhile to understand the Extreme Value Theorem."},
  {"id": "seg_00108", "translation": "Extreme Value Theorem: If the function "},
  {"id": "seg_00109", "translation": " is continuous on the closed interval [a, b], then there must exist two points c and d in this interval such that "},
  {"id": "seg_00110", "translation": " is the absolute maximum and "},
  {"id": "seg_00111", "translation": " is the absolute minimum."},
  {"id": "seg_00112", "translation": "The figure below illustrates the Extreme Value Theorem."},
  {"id": "seg_00113", "translation": "My takeaways from studying this theorem are: (1) Although the absolute extrema on a closed interval are guaranteed to be attained, they need not be unique; (2) Both conditions — \"continuous\" and \"closed interval\" — are indispensable."},
  {"id": "seg_00114", "translation": "The figures below show what happens when one of these two conditions — continuity and a closed interval — is missing, causing the Extreme Value Theorem to fail."},
  {"id": "seg_00115", "translation": "As the figure shows, the function on the left has no maximum value, and neither does the function on the right. The reason: the function on the left is discontinuous, and the function on the right is defined on an open interval."},
  {"id": "seg_00116", "translation": "With the question of existence settled, our next task is to find the extreme points based on their characteristics. For a continuous function, global extrema on a closed interval are guaranteed to exist. In general, global extrema are selected from among the many local extrema, so finding the local extrema first becomes the"},
  {"id": "seg_00117", "translation": "Mastering Calculus"},
  {"id": "seg_00118", "translation": "immediate priority. So what do local extreme points look like? Consider the following theorem:"},
  {"id": "seg_00119", "translation": "Fermat's Theorem"},
  {"id": "seg_00120", "translation": "If c is a local extreme point of the function "},
  {"id": "seg_00121", "translation": " and "},
  {"id": "seg_00122", "translation": " exists, then:"},
  {"id": "seg_00123", "translation": "Proof: Without loss of generality, assume "},
  {"id": "seg_00124", "translation": " is a "},
  {"id": "seg_00125", "translation": " local maximum of f; the case of a local minimum follows by the same argument."},
  {"id": "seg_00126", "translation": " being a local maximum means that on some small neighborhood containing c, the following inequality holds:"},
  {"id": "seg_00127", "translation": "Therefore, we have:"},
  {"id": "seg_00128", "translation": "In the expression above, since the numerator is non-positive and the denominator is negative,"},
  {"id": "seg_00129", "translation": ". Similarly, we have:"},
  {"id": "seg_00130", "translation": "We have now established that the left-hand and right-hand derivatives of f at c are on opposite sides of zero. Since "},
  {"id": "seg_00131", "translation": " exists, the left-hand and right-hand derivatives must be equal. The only possibility is:"},
  {"id": "seg_00132", "translation": "."},
  {"id": "seg_00133", "translation": "Note: Fermat's Theorem only tells you that if a local extreme point has a derivative, then that derivative equals 0. It does not say that all local extreme points have a derivative equal to 0. Why? Because some local extreme points have no derivative at all! These points where the derivative does not exist, together with the points where the derivative equals 0, are collectively called critical points of the function (Critical Point)."},
  {"id": "seg_00134", "translation": "After all this work, we've finally found a foothold for computing extrema! First, identify the critical points of the function — those where the derivative does not exist or equals 0; then compare the function values at the interval endpoints and the critical points to determine the global and local extrema."},
  {"id": "seg_00135", "translation": "The reason we separately consider function values at the interval endpoints is that, while endpoints do not satisfy the definition of a local extreme point, they can still be global extreme points. For example, a strictly monotone function always attains its global extrema at the endpoints, with no local extrema in the interior."},
  {"id": "seg_00136", "translation": "Now, how do we determine whether a critical point we've worked hard to find is a local maximum or a local minimum? To answer this, we turn once again to the derivative — the local trend. As we introduced in the previous chapter, the sign of the derivative at each point determines whether the function is rising or falling there. From"},
  {"id": "seg_00137", "translation": "Chapter 4 | What Are Derivatives Good For?"},
  {"id": "seg_00138", "translation": "this it follows readily that if the derivative of a function is positive throughout some interval, then f is increasing on that interval. Conversely, if the derivative is negative, f is decreasing."},
  {"id": "seg_00139", "translation": "Equivalently, the sign of the slope of the tangent line determines whether the function is increasing or decreasing."},
  {"id": "seg_00140", "translation": "As shown in the figure, the function is increasing on segments AB and CD, and accordingly its tangent slope — i.e., its derivative — is positive on those segments. On segment BC the derivative is negative, so the function is decreasing there."},
  {"id": "seg_00141", "translation": "Clearly, the derivative of the function equals 0 at both B and C, which means both B and C are relative extreme points of the function."},
  {"id": "seg_00142", "translation": "As the function passes through B, its derivative goes from positive to zero to negative. Correspondingly, the function changes from increasing to decreasing. Therefore, B is a relative maximum."},
  {"id": "seg_00143", "translation": "As the function passes through C, its derivative goes from negative to zero to positive. Correspondingly, the function changes from decreasing before C to increasing after C. Therefore, C is a relative minimum of the function."},
  {"id": "seg_00144", "translation": "Conclusion: If the derivative changes from positive to negative on either side of a critical point, that critical point is a local maximum. Conversely, if the derivative changes from negative to positive on either side of a critical point, that critical point is a local minimum."},
  {"id": "seg_00145", "translation": "At this point, the strategy for finding extrema is essentially in hand. Let's put our newly acquired skills to work and see how they perform."},
  {"id": "seg_00146", "translation": "Example 4-5)  "},
  {"id": "seg_00147", "translation": "Find the absolute extrema of f(x) = 2x³ − 3x² − 12x on the interval [−2, 3]."},
  {"id": "seg_00148", "translation": "Solution: Following the standard procedure, we first find the critical points:"},
