  {"id": "seg_00165", "translation": "4.3  Linear Approximation (Linear Approximation)"},
  {"id": "seg_00166", "translation": "As introduced earlier, calculus handles curves by the divide-and-conquer approach — breaking the curve into many small segments and treating each segment as a straight line. Of course, this approximation is not exact. But when the number of segments grows infinitely large, the result of this linear treatment can be regarded as exact."},
  {"id": "seg_00167", "translation": "So which straight line should we choose as the representative approximation for a curve? Since the local trend of a curve at a given point is in the direction of the tangent line, it is natural to use the tangent line at that point to represent the curve. In general, the approximation is better the closer you are to that specific point."},
  {"id": "seg_00168", "translation": "As shown in the figure, linear approximation means using a linear function to approximately represent "},
  {"id": "seg_00169", "translation": " near the point a. The equation of the tangent line at a is:"},
  {"id": "seg_00170", "translation": "Therefore, the linear approximation near a is:"},
  {"id": "seg_00171", "translation": "Linear approximation is a simple approach, but also a last resort. Using a quadratic or higher-degree function as the approximating tool would certainly be more accurate, but would require much more effort. Though imperfect, this method is quite practical. Some have even given it the grander name of \"linear approximation\" — but it's the same idea."},
  {"id": "seg_00172", "translation": "Let's work through an example to illustrate linear approximation."},
  {"id": "seg_00173", "translation": "Example 4-7)  "},
  {"id": "seg_00174", "translation": "Find the linear approximation of f(x) = ∛x at x = 27, and use it to estimate ∛28 (to four decimal places). Compare the estimate with the exact value."},
  {"id": "seg_00175", "translation": "Solution: From the problem, f(27) = 3, and the derivative of f is:"},
  {"id": "seg_00176", "translation": "Mastering Calculus"},
  {"id": "seg_00177", "translation": "So the desired linear approximation is:"},
  {"id": "seg_00178", "translation": "On the other hand, a direct calculation with a calculator gives:"},
  {"id": "seg_00179", "translation": ". We can see that the estimated value is slightly larger than the exact value. A calculation shows that the accuracy is "},
  {"id": "seg_00180", "translation": "."},
  {"id": "seg_00181", "translation": "Now let's connect two ideas — linear approximation and differentials. Revisit the figure introducing function differentials:"},
  {"id": "seg_00182", "translation": "We know the linear approximation at a is:"},
  {"id": "seg_00183", "translation": "Its corresponding point is R. The exact value is:"},
  {"id": "seg_00184", "translation": "Its corresponding point on the graph is Q. The difference between the approximation and the exact value is (dy − Δy). Clearly, the smaller dx is, the smaller this error becomes."},
  {"id": "seg_00185", "translation": "Linear approximation may not look complicated, but it can sometimes be inconvenient, and with the rapid development of computing technology its practical utility is diminishing. Nevertheless, we devote a separate section to it for two reasons: first, the problem-solving philosophy of simplifying the complex is a fundamental technique in calculus and can guide our everyday work as well; second, this seemingly simple method was once enormously valuable and represents the hard work of many pioneers — we owe them our respect!"},
  {"id": "seg_00186", "translation": "Chapter 4 | What Are Derivatives Good For?"},
  {"id": "seg_00187", "translation": "4.4  Feeling Your Way Across — Newton's Method"},
  {"id": "seg_00188", "translation": "Most elementary school students can solve a linear equation quite competently. And virtually every high school student can write down the quadratic formula. But what about something more complex? For example:"},
  {"id": "seg_00189", "translation": "Feeling a bit lost? What about something even more complex? For example:"},
  {"id": "seg_00190", "translation": "If someone asked you to produce a formula for solving such an equation, you'd probably refuse — and rightly so! Even if you tracked down a mathematician to do the job, they couldn't manage it either. The vast majority of equations that arise in applied sciences cannot be solved by a closed-form formula."},
  {"id": "seg_00191", "translation": "Mathematical pioneers long ago recognized that many equations cannot be solved exactly. But they didn't give up — they devised every possible means to seek approximate solutions instead. Stepping back and making peace with imperfection, embracing the approximate — that, too, is a great life wisdom!"},
  {"id": "seg_00192", "translation": "The master Newton devised an elegant approach for finding approximate solutions to equations. The method Newton used is the standard calculus technique: solving a nonlinear problem with linear tools."},
  {"id": "seg_00193", "translation": "The idea is as follows:"},
  {"id": "seg_00194", "translation": "1) As shown in the figure, suppose our task is to find the root r of "},
  {"id": "seg_00195", "translation": ". With no starting point, we simply guess some x₁. Almost certainly, x₁ is not the r we're looking for."},
  {"id": "seg_00196", "translation": "2) Next, we find the tangent line L to the curve at x₁. Since it's a straight line, we can easily find the point x₂ where L crosses the x-axis."},
  {"id": "seg_00197", "translation": "3) Naturally, x₂ is probably not r either. But since the tangent direction is the local trend of the function, representing the direction "},
  {"id": "seg_00198", "translation": " curves near x₁, we know that even though x₂ is not r, it should be closer to r than x₁ was."},
  {"id": "seg_00199", "translation": "4) Find the tangent line to the curve at x₂ and locate its intersection with the x-axis, x₃. x₃ is closer to r than x₂."},
  {"id": "seg_00200", "translation": "5) Repeating the above steps yields x₁, x₂, x₃, …, xₙ, …"},
  {"id": "seg_00201", "translation": "Mastering Calculus"},
  {"id": "seg_00202", "translation": "From the figure it is easy to see:"},
  {"id": "seg_00203", "translation": "Generalizing:"},
  {"id": "seg_00204", "translation": "That is:"},
  {"id": "seg_00205", "translation": "7) Conclusion: The larger n is, the closer xₙ is to r. In other words:"},
  {"id": "seg_00206", "translation": "Don't be discouraged by the sight of a limit — the mathematical idea here is worth pondering carefully. Now let's put it to use."},
  {"id": "seg_00207", "translation": "Example 4-8)  "},
  {"id": "seg_00208", "translation": "Starting from x₁ = 2, find an approximate root of the equation x³ − 2x − 5 = 0 (accurate to four decimal places)."},
  {"id": "seg_00209", "translation": "Solution: Let "},
  {"id": "seg_00210", "translation": "So, following Newton's method, we have:"},
  {"id": "seg_00211", "translation": "Therefore:"},
  {"id": "seg_00212", "translation": "How accurate is x₃? Using a calculator gives:"},
  {"id": "seg_00213", "translation": ". As you can see, x₃ is remarkably accurate. And why did we choose this particular example? Remember — this problem is the very example Newton himself used in the paper that introduced Newton's Method!"},
  {"id": "seg_00214", "translation": "Although Newton's Method is extremely useful, applying it haphazardly can sometimes lead you into"},
  {"id": "seg_00215", "translation": "Chapter 4 | What Are Derivatives Good For?"},
  {"id": "seg_00216", "translation": "trouble, failing to achieve the desired result. See the figure below:"},
  {"id": "seg_00217", "translation": "x₁ looks reasonable, but starting from x₂ the iterates drift further and further from r. Why? Because in Newton's Method, the choice of the first guess x₁ is a skill in itself!"},
  {"id": "seg_00218", "translation": "Just as in the master's own example, he chose x₁ = 2 — why not 0, 1, or −1? The comparison makes it clear: f(0) = −5, f(1) = −6, f(−1) = −4, and f(2) = −1. Naturally, you'd pick the value whose function value is closest to 0, and that's 2."},
  {"id": "seg_00219", "translation": "The spirit of Newton's Method can be captured in a classic saying: feel your way across the river, stone by stone. But which stone to step on first — that takes real judgment."},
  {"id": "seg_00220", "translation": "In today's world of rapidly advancing AI, Newton's Method has enormous practical significance. Many advanced calculators that students use can solve all kinds of nonstandard equations, and the underlying principle in most of them is Newton's Method."},
  {"id": "seg_00221", "translation": "Let's work through another example to get familiar with the process."},
  {"id": "seg_00222", "translation": "Example 4-9)  "},
  {"id": "seg_00223", "translation": "Use Newton's Method to find the root of the equation cos x − sin x = x, accurate to four decimal places."},
  {"id": "seg_00224", "translation": "Solution: Let's first sketch "},
