  {"id": "seg_00246", "translation": "Proof of the theorem: We consider three cases."},
  {"id": "seg_00247", "translation": "Chapter 4 | What Are Derivatives Good For?"},
  {"id": "seg_00248", "translation": "Case 1: If "},
  {"id": "seg_00249", "translation": " for every x in [a, b], then the graph of f(x) is a horizontal line, and the tangent at every differentiable point in (a, b) is parallel to the x-axis. Any point c will satisfy:"},
  {"id": "seg_00250", "translation": "."},
  {"id": "seg_00251", "translation": "Case 2: If some point in (a, b) has a function value greater than the endpoint values, then by the Extreme Value Theorem there must exist a point c in (a, b) such that "},
  {"id": "seg_00252", "translation": " is the maximum value of f(x) on [a, b]. By definition, "},
  {"id": "seg_00253", "translation": " is also a relative maximum, and since f(x) is differentiable at c, by Fermat's Theorem we conclude:"},
  {"id": "seg_00254", "translation": "."},
  {"id": "seg_00255", "translation": "Case 3: If some point in (a, b) has a function value less than the endpoint values, by the same argument as in Case 2 we can conclude: there exists a point c in (a, b) satisfying:"},
  {"id": "seg_00256", "translation": "."},
  {"id": "seg_00257", "translation": "The figure above illustrates several scenarios in which Rolle's Theorem holds. As the figure shows, the geometric meaning of Rolle's Theorem is: when the function values at the endpoints are equal, there exists a point c in (a, b) at which the tangent is parallel to the x-axis."},
  {"id": "seg_00258", "translation": "Since the endpoint values are equal, the line connecting them is also parallel to the x-axis. Rolle's Theorem is therefore equivalent to saying there exists a point c in (a, b) where the tangent is parallel to the line connecting the endpoints. Naturally, we ask: does this conclusion hold when the endpoint values are unequal? The answer is yes!"},
  {"id": "seg_00259", "translation": "Lagrange's Mean Value Theorem"},
  {"id": "seg_00260", "translation": "Suppose the function "},
