  {"id": "seg_00265", "translation": "Proof: The key insight is that we just proved Rolle's Theorem, and the right-hand side of the equation we need to prove is the slope of the line connecting the"},
  {"id": "seg_00266", "translation": "Mastering Calculus"},
  {"id": "seg_00267", "translation": "endpoints. So we would very much like to find a function that is related to both the endpoints and to "},
  {"id": "seg_00268", "translation": ", while having equal values at the two endpoints."},
  {"id": "seg_00269", "translation": "If we define a new function "},
  {"id": "seg_00270", "translation": " as the difference between "},
  {"id": "seg_00271", "translation": " and the y-value on the line connecting the endpoints, then this new function's values at both endpoints are 0. Can we apply Rolle's Theorem to it?"},
  {"id": "seg_00272", "translation": "We know that the equation of the line connecting (a, f(a)) and (b, f(b)) is:"},
  {"id": "seg_00273", "translation": "Therefore, we define:"},
  {"id": "seg_00274", "translation": "What are the properties of this new g(x)? Not only is it continuous on [a, b] and differentiable on (a, b), but more importantly:"},
  {"id": "seg_00275", "translation": ", so all the conditions for Rolle's Theorem are satisfied. Therefore, there must exist a point c in (a, b) such that:"},
  {"id": "seg_00276", "translation": ". Substituting this into the defining equation above:"},
  {"id": "seg_00277", "translation": "In this proof, the technique of constructing the function "},
  {"id": "seg_00278", "translation": " tailor-made to apply Rolle's Theorem is a method commonly used in the creative work of great mathematicians throughout history, and it carries a very high level of technical sophistication."},
  {"id": "seg_00279", "translation": "The algebraic meaning of the Mean Value Theorem is that there exists a point c in (a, b) such that the instantaneous rate of change of "},
  {"id": "seg_00280", "translation": " at c equals the average rate of change of "},
  {"id": "seg_00281", "translation": " over the entire interval [a, b]."},
  {"id": "seg_00282", "translation": "The geometric meaning of the Mean Value Theorem is that there exists a point c in (a, b) at which the tangent to the function is parallel to the line connecting the endpoints. Please refer to the figure below:"},
  {"id": "seg_00283", "translation": "As shown above, the left figure shows a case where one point c satisfies the Mean Value Theorem; the right figure shows a case where two points c satisfy the Mean Value Theorem."},
  {"id": "seg_00284", "translation": "Chapter 4 | What Are Derivatives Good For?"},
  {"id": "seg_00285", "translation": "Let's work through two problems to get a feel for it:"},
  {"id": "seg_00286", "translation": "Example 4-10)  "},
  {"id": "seg_00287", "translation": "Verify that f(x) = 2x² − 3x + 1 satisfies the Mean Value Theorem on the interval [0, 2]."},
  {"id": "seg_00288", "translation": "Solution: Our task is to find a c in [0, 2] such that:"},
  {"id": "seg_00289", "translation": "Note that:"},
  {"id": "seg_00290", "translation": ", so we just need the following equation in c to have a solution:"},
  {"id": "seg_00291", "translation": "The equation above clearly has the solution c = 1."},
  {"id": "seg_00292", "translation": "Sometimes a problem can come at you from a different angle — see the example below."},
  {"id": "seg_00293", "translation": "Example 4-11)  "},
  {"id": "seg_00294", "translation": "Given that f(x) is differentiable everywhere, with f′(x) < 9 and f(1) = −8. Find the maximum possible value of f(3)."},
  {"id": "seg_00295", "translation": "Solution: By the Mean Value Theorem, we know there must exist a point c in (1, 3) such that:"},
  {"id": "seg_00296", "translation": "And since "},
  {"id": "seg_00297", "translation": ", we have:"},
  {"id": "seg_00298", "translation": "Mastering Calculus"},
  {"id": "seg_00299", "translation": "So:"},
  {"id": "seg_00300", "translation": ", i.e., "},
  {"id": "seg_00301", "translation": ". Therefore, the maximum possible value of "},
  {"id": "seg_00302", "translation": " is 10."},
  {"id": "seg_00303", "translation": "On one hand, we can prove Lagrange's theorem from Rolle's theorem; on the other, Rolle's theorem can be seen as a special case of Lagrange's theorem. In fact, Lagrange's theorem can itself be seen as a special case of another famous result — the Cauchy Mean Value Theorem."},
  {"id": "seg_00304", "translation": "Cauchy's Mean Value Theorem"},
  {"id": "seg_00305", "translation": "Suppose the functions "},
  {"id": "seg_00306", "translation": " are continuous on [a, b] and differentiable on (a, b), with "},
  {"id": "seg_00307", "translation": ". Then there must exist a "},
  {"id": "seg_00308", "translation": " satisfying:"},
  {"id": "seg_00309", "translation": "Cauchy's Mean Value Theorem can likewise be derived from Rolle's theorem using the same method used to prove Lagrange's theorem. In practice, Cauchy's Mean Value Theorem is most often applied to curves described by parametric equations:"},
  {"id": "seg_00310", "translation": "We can therefore say that both Lagrange's theorem and Cauchy's Mean Value Theorem are generalizations of Rolle's theorem. In practice, Cauchy's Mean Value Theorem does not appear on exams very often, so as a student it's enough to know what it looks like."},
  {"id": "seg_00311", "translation": "Rolle's theorem and Lagrange's theorem both shed light, to varying degrees, on certain features of a function's graph over a given interval — for example, the direction of the tangent. Based on the sign of the derivative over some interval, we can tell whether the function is increasing or decreasing there."},
  {"id": "seg_00312", "translation": "But even among increasing functions, there is a clear difference between the two types "},
  {"id": "seg_00313", "translation": " and "},
  {"id": "seg_00314", "translation": " shown in the figure:"},
  {"id": "seg_00315", "translation": "We typically call the left-hand graph — opening upward like a bowl — concave up, and the right-hand"},
  {"id": "seg_00316", "translation": "Chapter 4 | What Are Derivatives Good For?"},
  {"id": "seg_00317", "translation": "graph — opening downward — concave down. In mathematical language: the function "},
  {"id": "seg_00318", "translation": " is concave up on (a, b), and the function "},
  {"id": "seg_00319", "translation": " is concave down on (a, b)."},
  {"id": "seg_00320", "translation": "It is worth noting that the Chinese and Western conventions for describing concavity differ. In Chinese, the convention follows \"which side bulges out,\" so a curve that bulges upward is called \"convex upward.\" The Western convention focuses on the direction of opening, which is the opposite of the bulge. So what Chinese calls \"convex upward\" is described in English as Concave Down, and what Chinese calls \"convex downward\" corresponds to Concave Up in English."},
  {"id": "seg_00321", "translation": "One clear geometric property of concave-down and concave-up functions is this: all tangent lines to a concave-down function lie above the graph; all tangent lines to a concave-up function lie below the graph."},
  {"id": "seg_00322", "translation": "So how do we determine whether a function's graph is concave up or concave down? The tool is the second derivative test."},
  {"id": "seg_00323", "translation": "If on the interval (a, b) the function f(x) satisfies:"},
  {"id": "seg_00324", "translation": ", then f(x) is concave up on that interval; if on the interval (a, b) the function f(x) satisfies:"},
  {"id": "seg_00325", "translation": ", then f(x) is concave down on that interval."},
  {"id": "seg_00326", "translation": "This test can be proved using the Mean Value Theorem, but due to space constraints we will not go into the details here."},
  {"id": "seg_00327", "translation": "With the second derivative test in hand, we have a new tool for dealing with extremum problems. Based on the sign of the second derivative, we can readily draw the following conclusion:"},
  {"id": "seg_00328", "translation": "If the function "},
  {"id": "seg_00329", "translation": " has a second derivative that is continuous near c, then:"},
  {"id": "seg_00330", "translation": "1) If "},
  {"id": "seg_00331", "translation": " and "},
  {"id": "seg_00332", "translation": ", then "},
  {"id": "seg_00333", "translation": " is a relative minimum of the function;"},
  {"id": "seg_00334", "translation": "2) If "},
  {"id": "seg_00335", "translation": " and "},
  {"id": "seg_00336", "translation": ", then "},
  {"id": "seg_00337", "translation": " is a relative maximum of the function."},
  {"id": "seg_00338", "translation": "This conclusion is geometrically very intuitive. Let me briefly explain the first case: since the second derivative is positive, the curve is concave up. Therefore, in the neighborhood of c, the tangent line lies below the graph; and since the tangent at c is horizontal, "},
  {"id": "seg_00339", "translation": " is a relative minimum of the function."},
  {"id": "seg_00340", "translation": "Mastering Calculus"},
  {"id": "seg_00341", "translation": "On one hand, when the function is concave up the tangent lies below the graph, and the extremum at a concave-up critical point is a relative minimum — this is consistent. On the other hand, when the function is concave down the tangent lies above the graph, and the extremum at a concave-down critical point is a relative maximum — also consistent."},
  {"id": "seg_00342", "translation": "To view concavity from a broader perspective, I'd like to draw your attention to another fact: for a concave-down function, any chord connecting two points on the graph lies below the graph. Conversely, for a concave-up function, any chord lies above the graph."},
  {"id": "seg_00343", "translation": "Having covered this section, when solving extremum problems in the future we can either: use the sign change of the first derivative on either side of a critical point to determine the increasing/decreasing behavior of the function near that point, thereby identifying whether the critical point is a local maximum or minimum; or, more directly, use the sign of the second derivative to classify the critical point."},
  {"id": "seg_00344", "translation": "Now, let's apply this to the familiar quadratic function "},
  {"id": "seg_00345", "translation": " for a more sophisticated summary:"},
  {"id": "seg_00346", "translation": "From "},
  {"id": "seg_00347", "translation": ", the critical point of y is "},
  {"id": "seg_00348", "translation": "("},
  {"id": "seg_00349", "translation": "). So when "},
  {"id": "seg_00350", "translation": ", since "},
  {"id": "seg_00351", "translation": ", y attains a minimum at the critical point; conversely, when "},
  {"id": "seg_00352", "translation": ", since "},
  {"id": "seg_00353", "translation": ", y attains a maximum at the critical point."},
  {"id": "seg_00354", "translation": "Let's look at an example."},
  {"id": "seg_00355", "translation": "Example 4-12)  "},
  {"id": "seg_00356", "translation": "Given that the derivative of f(x) is f′(x) = (x − 1)eˣ, find the critical points of the function and classify each one."},
  {"id": "seg_00357", "translation": "Solution: Following the standard approach, set the derivative equal to 0 — we find that "},
  {"id": "seg_00358", "translation": " has exactly one critical point, at x = 1."},
  {"id": "seg_00359", "translation": "Method 1: When "},
  {"id": "seg_00360", "translation": ","},
  {"id": "seg_00361", "translation": ", so f(x) is decreasing; when "},
  {"id": "seg_00362", "translation": ","},
  {"id": "seg_00363", "translation": ", so f(x) is increasing."},
  {"id": "seg_00364", "translation": "Chapter 4 | What Are Derivatives Good For?"},
  {"id": "seg_00365", "translation": "Therefore, the critical point c = 1 is a local minimum."},
  {"id": "seg_00366", "translation": "Method 2: Computing the second derivative gives "},
  {"id": "seg_00367", "translation": ", so "},
  {"id": "seg_00368", "translation": ". Therefore, x = 1 is a local minimum."},
  {"id": "seg_00369", "translation": "Interesting, right? On the subject of concavity, there is one more concept to introduce with some fanfare."},
  {"id": "seg_00370", "translation": "Point of Inflection"},
  {"id": "seg_00371", "translation": "If the function "},
  {"id": "seg_00372", "translation": " has a continuous second derivative that changes sign at the point a, then a is called a point of inflection (inflection point) of "},
  {"id": "seg_00373", "translation": "."},
  {"id": "seg_00374", "translation": "Key insights on inflection points:"},
  {"id": "seg_00375", "translation": "1) On either side of an inflection point, the function changes from concave down to concave up, or vice versa;"},
  {"id": "seg_00376", "translation": "2) At an inflection point, the second derivative is either 0 or does not exist."},
  {"id": "seg_00377", "translation": "We just learned about critical points, and now we have inflection points. Let's compare them: a critical point is a point where the derivative is 0 or does not exist — it is a candidate for an extremum. An inflection point is a point where the second derivative changes sign; however, note that the second derivative being 0 or nonexistent is only a necessary condition for a point to be an inflection point, not a sufficient one. Just as continuity is a necessary but not sufficient condition for differentiability."},
  {"id": "seg_00378", "translation": "At this point, we should be able to describe the local behavior of a function's graph fairly clearly. The way a graph evolves is a bit like the basic strokes in Chinese calligraphy — horizontal, vertical, diagonal sweeps. Similarly, a function's graph is made up of just a few basic shapes: a straight-line rise (or fall) like \"/\"; a concave-down rise (or fall) like the left half (or right half) of a \"∩\"; and a concave-up fall (or rise) like the left half (or right half) of a \"∪\"."},
  {"id": "seg_00379", "translation": "With the help of derivatives, we can understand the basic features of a function — its increasing/decreasing behavior and its concavity. Adding in asymptotes, we can sketch a reasonably accurate graph even for fairly complex functions."},
  {"id": "seg_00380", "translation": "Putting it all together, here is a standard checklist for sketching a proper function graph:"},
  {"id": "seg_00381", "translation": "1) Note the domain of the function;"},
  {"id": "seg_00382", "translation": "2) Find the intercepts with the coordinate axes;"},
  {"id": "seg_00383", "translation": "3) Check for symmetry (even/odd functions);"},
  {"id": "seg_00384", "translation": "4) Look for asymptotes;"},
  {"id": "seg_00385", "translation": "5) Find the relative extrema;"},
  {"id": "seg_00386", "translation": "6) Note intervals of increase/decrease and concavity."},
  {"id": "seg_00387", "translation": "Example 4-13)  "},
  {"id": "seg_00388", "translation": "Sketch the graph of the following function:"},
  {"id": "seg_00389", "translation": "Mastering Calculus"},
