  {"id": "seg_00393", "translation": "2) Clearly, the function intersects the coordinate axes only at the origin."},
  {"id": "seg_00394", "translation": "3) Since "},
  {"id": "seg_00395", "translation": ", the function is even and symmetric about the y-axis."},
  {"id": "seg_00396", "translation": "4) Because:"},
  {"id": "seg_00397", "translation": "the function has a horizontal asymptote y = 3/2. And because:"},
  {"id": "seg_00398", "translation": "the function has two vertical asymptotes: x = ±√(5/2)."},
  {"id": "seg_00399", "translation": "5) Find the critical points, "},
  {"id": "seg_00400", "translation": ":"},
  {"id": "seg_00401", "translation": "We see that 0 is the only critical point of "},
  {"id": "seg_00402", "translation": "; it is easy to check that the derivative changes from positive to negative at 0, which means 0 is a relative maximum."},
  {"id": "seg_00403", "translation": "Next, analyze concavity:"},
  {"id": "seg_00404", "translation": "Step 1, compute the second derivative:"},
  {"id": "seg_00405", "translation": "Step 2, on the interval (−√(5/2), √(5/2)),"},
  {"id": "seg_00406", "translation": ", so f(x) is concave down;"},
  {"id": "seg_00407", "translation": "Chapter 4 | What Are Derivatives Good For?"},
  {"id": "seg_00408", "translation": "and on the intervals (−∞, −√(5/2)) and (√(5/2), +∞),"},
  {"id": "seg_00409", "translation": ", so the function is concave up."},
  {"id": "seg_00410", "translation": "Putting it all together, we can sketch the graph of this function as follows:"},
  {"id": "seg_00411", "translation": "4.6  Finding the Root — Antiderivatives (Antiderivative)"},
  {"id": "seg_00412", "translation": "When we describe how thoroughly someone knows a piece of text, we sometimes say they can recite it forwards and backwards. If you can apply the derivative formulas you've learned in reverse — that is, given a derivative, work out which function it came from — you have achieved a similar mastery. In other words, if you spot an \"unclaimed\" derivative in the wild, you can quickly answer the question \"which function does this derivative belong to?\" This is a fundamental skill in calculus."},
  {"id": "seg_00413", "translation": "For example, from the formula "},
  {"id": "seg_00414", "translation": ", you can easily say that "},
  {"id": "seg_00415", "translation": " is the derivative of "},
  {"id": "seg_00416", "translation": "."},
  {"id": "seg_00417", "translation": "Because the process of finding the original function from its derivative is the exact reverse of differentiation, it has an aptly suggestive name: antiderivative."},
  {"id": "seg_00418", "translation": "For example, saying that 2x is the derivative of x² is the same as saying x² is the antiderivative of 2x."},
  {"id": "seg_00419", "translation": "In general, when we say "},
  {"id": "seg_00420", "translation": " is the antiderivative of "},
  {"id": "seg_00421", "translation": ", we mean:"},
  {"id": "seg_00422", "translation": "As an experienced differentiator, you naturally know that not only "},
  {"id": "seg_00423", "translation": ", but any function of the form "},
  {"id": "seg_00424", "translation": " (where C is a constant) has derivative "},
  {"id": "seg_00425", "translation": ". In other words, the antiderivative of "},
